I’m beginning a series of big canvases! Some thoughts on painting large-scale:

- Creating the base color is SO MUCH FUN. It’s a great place to try interesting layering and color combinations. 

- I have to stand waaay back to check how the painting’s going. I even borrowed the spot of a painting in our living room so I could look from further away - it was amazing how a piece reads differently at a distance!

- It’s unearthing some old fears of mine: What if no one wants a painting this big / opinionated / expensive? Where will I store them all if they don’t sell? Can I even fill up all this canvas space in a meaningful way? How much paint is this going to take?? 🤣

.

As I created this painting, I struggled with deciding what to paint alongside the vase. First I tried a bird nest, then a nest and a hawk’s feather, but neither of those felt quite right as the painting developed. Then I painted in a single blue jay feather and the simplicity felt just right. I love the bold blue color and I have special memories of blue jays in my childhood backyard. I trained them to come when I whistled and gave them treats 🪶 Do you have any meaningful memories of birds?

“The Blue Feather” 36x36, will be available in my shop tomorrow at 7am pst/10am est. Feel free to hop on my email list for a reminder + direct link when it goes live in the morning!

This is the stage in my painting process when I obscure things with intuitive layers of color. I love the hazy effects this creates! Then I slowly select elements to bring back into “focus”. For this painting, I had a strong sense that there needed to be more light blue in the background and that it needed to somehow feel watery, like a beautiful, sunny spring rain. I can’t wait to see how she ends up!

Some of the tools + materials I used to prep this big canvas:

>  Golden + Liquitex fluid acrylics
> Spray bottle (to add a bit more flow to the paint on my palette and canvas)
> Catalyst silicone wedge tool (I like how it exposes the textures below when scraping)
> Small squeegee (I like its soft, broad strokes for quick, expressive movement)

I painted this background with nothing in mind but to create some depth + layers + textures. Now that it’s dry and up on my easel, those marks are already suggesting interesting movement and compositions to me! ✨

I used to be bummed by the messy middle of my paintings… Now I actively use that mushy/undefined stage to freely add textural marks, colors that don’t *quite* make sense, and layers to build up depth.  It’s really freeing to remember that this isn’t where the piece is going to stay, but to enjoy its messiness anyway 🙌🏼 I know that this is just the beginning, and I’ll tighten things up as the painting develops and decides exactly how it wants to be ✨
